mōmen, inis, n. for movimen, from moveo. Movement, motion: e salso consurgere momine ponti, i. e.
from the salt billows, Lucr. 6, 474; so also id. 2, 632, and 4, 179; v. Lachm. (where others read numine); cf. id. 3, 144.— Weight, momentum; importance, moment (ante- and postclass.): momine parvo moveri, Lucr. 3, 188: nullius mominis esse,
to be of no consequence, of no moment, Arn. 2, 77.—* A moment of time, Manil. 3, 675.
